      "SME lending has been a central part of the strategy. Tiered credit products aimed at businesses historically underserved by Liberian banks — which have tended to concentrate lending on government contractors, established importers, and multinational clients — have widened access for smaller firms. Liberian commercial banks more broadly have been working to grow SME books while keeping non-performing loans in check.",
      "Digital banking has been a second pillar. App-based platforms have reduced the cost of serving low-balance customers and extended services to clients in counties without physical branches, with a growing share of retail transactions and loan applications now initiated on mobile. The shift mirrors the broader move toward mobile-first financial services across Liberia.",
      "The obstacles to deeper financial inclusion are real. Interest rates on Ecobank's commercial loans range from 16% to 21% annually — a reflection of the CBL's 16.25% policy rate, high operational costs, and the absence of a functioning credit bureau in Liberia. Without reliable credit history data, banks must price risk conservatively. The CBL has been working with the World Bank to establish a national credit bureau since 2022; the system is now partially operational, but coverage remains limited to borrowers who have previously interacted with the formal banking system — excluding the majority of the population the bureau is meant to serve.",
