      "The African Development Bank's Board of Directors approved a $28 million concessional loan to Liberia on March 10 for the rehabilitation of 320 kilometres of rural feeder roads in five agricultural counties: Lofa, Nimba, Bong, Margibi, and Grand Bassa. The loan, at a 0.75% annual interest rate with a 40-year repayment period and 10-year grace period, will fund the grading, gravelling, and drainage improvement of roads connecting smallholder farming communities to market towns and the national road network. The Ministry of Public Works will execute the project with supervision from an AfDB-appointed engineering firm.",
      "Rural road access is among the most consistently cited constraints on agricultural productivity in Liberia. During the rainy season — which runs from May through October — unpaved feeder roads in many counties become impassable, cutting farming communities off from markets for weeks at a time. Produce that cannot reach markets within 24–48 hours of harvest deteriorates rapidly in Liberia's tropical climate. The Food and Agriculture Organization estimates that post-harvest losses in Liberia's fruit and vegetable sectors reach 30–40% annually, with inadequate road access accounting for a significant share of those losses.",
      "In Lofa County, where the AfDB project will fund approximately 85 kilometres of rehabilitation, cocoa and coffee farmers in the Foya, Voinjama, and Kolahun districts have for years relied on motorcycle taxis and informal traders to move produce to collection points, incurring transport costs that can represent 20–25% of their farm gate revenue. A rehabilitated road connecting Foya to the national highway would cut transport costs by an estimated 60% and open access to processors in Monrovia who currently find Lofa supply chains too unreliable to depend on.",
