      "Gross international reserves are the central bank's foreign exchange holdings available for balance-of-payments purposes, including foreign currency assets, SDR holdings, and gold. The IMF's standard adequacy benchmark suggests that three months of import cover represents a minimum adequate level for countries like Liberia with limited external financing flexibility. At roughly two months, Liberia sits below that threshold — so while the buffer has improved, it remains thin rather than comfortable.",
